title: "Social Security Planning | Maximize Your Benefits | Capital Wealth"
description: "Optimize your Social Security benefits with strategic claiming strategies. Expert guidance to maximize your lifetime Social Security income."
breadcrumbs:
  - { name: "Home", url: "/" }
  - { name: "Services", url: "/services/" }
  - { name: "Social Security Planning", url: "/services/social-security/" }
faqSchema:
  - question: "When should I claim Social Security benefits?"
    answer: "The optimal claiming age depends on your health, financial situation, and spousal benefits. You can claim as early as 62 (with reduced benefits), at full retirement age (100% benefits), or delay until 70 (with delayed retirement credits up to 132% of your benefit)."
  - question: "What is the Social Security break-even age?"
    answer: "The break-even age is when total benefits from delaying equal total benefits from claiming early. This typically occurs in your early 80s, but varies based on your specific benefit amount and claiming strategy."
  - question: "How does Social Security affect my taxes in retirement?"
    answer: "Up to 85% of Social Security benefits may be taxable depending on your combined income. Strategic income planning can help minimize Social Security taxes and keep more of your benefits."
  - question: "What are spousal Social Security benefits?"
    answer: "A spouse can receive up to 50% of the higher-earning spouse's full retirement benefit, or their own benefit if higher. Strategic claiming coordination between spouses can maximize total household Social Security income."
  - question: "Can I work and collect Social Security at the same time?"
    answer: "Yes, but if you're under full retirement age, earnings above certain thresholds will reduce your benefits temporarily. After full retirement age, you can earn any amount without penalty."
  - question: "What happens to Social Security benefits when I die?"
    answer: "A surviving spouse can receive 100% of the deceased spouse's benefit (if higher than their own). Proper claiming strategies can maximize the survivor benefit for the remaining spouse."
