<section class="ep-faq">
  <div class="ep-faq-inner">
    <div>
      <span class="ep-chapter-label">Common Questions</span>
      <h2 class="ep-faq-title">Social Security FAQ</h2>
      <p class="ep-faq-sub">Learn about strategic Social Security claiming to maximize your lifetime benefits.</p>
      <a href="/contact/" class="ep-btn-ghost">Ask About Social Security</a>
    </div>
    <div>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">When should I claim Social Security benefits? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>The optimal claiming age depends on your health, financial situation, and spousal benefits. You can claim as early as 62 (with reduced benefits), at full retirement age (100% benefits), or delay until 70 (with delayed retirement credits up to 132% of your benefit).</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">What is the Social Security break-even age? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>The break-even age is when total benefits from delaying equal total benefits from claiming early. This typically occurs in your early 80s, but varies based on your specific benefit amount and claiming strategy.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">How does Social Security affect my taxes in retirement? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Up to 85% of Social Security benefits may be taxable depending on your combined income. Strategic income planning can help minimize Social Security taxes and keep more of your benefits.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">What are spousal Social Security benefits? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>A spouse can receive up to 50% of the higher-earning spouse's full retirement benefit, or their own benefit if higher. Strategic claiming coordination between spouses can maximize total household Social Security income.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">Can I work and collect Social Security at the same time? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Yes, but if you're under full retirement age, earnings above certain thresholds will reduce your benefits temporarily. After full retirement age, you can earn any amount without penalty.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">What happens to Social Security benefits when I die? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>A surviving spouse can receive 100% of the deceased spouse's benefit (if higher than their own). Proper claiming strategies can maximize the survivor benefit for the remaining spouse.</p></div>
      </button>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

